Please note there is an approximate two-week delay between the inspection and the posting of the inspection data online.

Routine

A routine inspection is a site visit that is comprehensive in nature and generally results in the scoring of the food facility. In grocery stores, only the deli\ food service area (and the areas of the store used to support the deli\ food service area) is graded. The remainder of the store is reported as a directed inspection. Therefore, there may be two inspections (one routine and one directed) for the same permit on the same date.


Reinspection

A reinspection is a site visit to verify compliance with an official notice of violation.


Other

An inspection type of other is a site visit that is limited in scope, such as a recall.

Major Violations

Under state law, major violations associated with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention risk factors require immediate corrective action, a suitable alternative, or the closure of the impacted areas of the food facility until compliance is achieved.

Directed

A directed inspection is a site visit that is limited in scope. A directed inspection does not result in the scoring of the food facility.


No Access

During the course of the site visit, the specialist was unable to complete an inspection. This may have occurred for a variety of reasons. For example, the facility may have not been open for business due to hours or dates of operation. The specialist may have lacked access to the property.


Closure

When a major violation cannot be immediately corrected, or a suitable alternative found, the food facility may be subject to closure in the impacted areas until the violation is corrected. The food facility must remain closed until written authorization to re-open is given by this department.
All major violations must be corrected or a suitable alternative before the facility is granted permission to re-open. Conditions that constitute an imminent health hazard and require the closure of the food facility include, but are not limited to, the following:

  • Sewage back-up,
  • Lack of potable hot/cold water under pressure,
  • Power outage for an extended period of time preventing proper holding temperatures of potentially hazardous foods,
  • Gross contamination of food contact surfaces,
  • Lack of valid public health permit,
  • Failure to improve a grade of "C" after 30 days, or
  • Serious and repeated risk factor violations


Re-open

This facility was granted permission to re-open by this Department after a period of closure. All major violations were corrected or a suitable alternative was in effect before the facility was allowed to re-open.
